  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "The legal history of money laundering prohibitions has several key developments:\n\n1. Early Origins:\n- Emerged as a concept in response to organized crime activities\n- Initially focused on concealing proceeds from illegal activities\n\n2. United States Developments:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970) - First major legislative effort to combat money laundering\n- Established reporting requirements for financial institutions\n- Required documentation of large cash transactions\n\n3. International Milestones:\n- 1988 Vienna Convention - First international treaty addressing money laundering related to drug trafficking\n- 1989 Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established\n- Developed international standards for combating money laundering\n\n4. Major Legislative Expansions:\n- U.S. Money Laundering Control Act (1986)\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001) - Significantly expanded anti-money laundering regulations\n- Expanded scope to include terrorism financing\n\n5. Global Regulatory Framework:\n- Increased international cooperation\n- Standardized reporting requirements\n- More comprehensive legal definitions of money laundering\n- Enhanced compliance mechanisms for financial institutions\n\n6. Recent Trends:\n- Cryptocurrency regulations\n- Enhanced digital transaction monitoring\n- Increased cross-border enforcement efforts\n\nThe legal framework continues evolving to address emerging financial technologies and criminal strategies.",
